<h1>Problem 648 - 2006 USAMO, P5 of 6</h1>
<h2 class='difficulty'>Difficulty: 8</h2>
<p>A mathematical frog jumps along the number line. The frog starts at \(1\), and jumps according to the following rule: if the frog is at integer \(n\), then it can jump either to \(n+1\) or to \(n + 2^{m_n+1}\) where \(2^{m_n}\) is the largest power of \(2\) that is a factor of \(n.\) Show that if \(k \geq 2\) is a positive integer and \(i\) is a nonnegative integer, then the minimum number of jumps needed to reach \(2^ik\) is greater than the minimum number of jumps needed to reach \(2^i.\)</p>
